I've been making bets on the Oscars for a decade and it's quite clear what the Academy is looking for when they vote on the best film. The Revenant has everything they like (unique production design, revenge story with a twist, amazing actors suffering in hard weather conditions for a long time, Inarritu as director and Lubezki as the best cinematographer of our time). Moreover, there is not real contestant this year. It seems like all production companies have given up when they saw The Revenant was coming. It has won all major awards from the Golden Globe to the Bafta. And finally, if as a layperson you watch all nominated movies, The Revenant demonstrates much higher amplitudes than the others regarding emotions, filming and acting.

On @Grok's suggestion, I'm updating on my previous forecast (1) to account for The Revenant winning the BAFTA best picture. Over the last 20 years (The timescale I've been using for the other award-based indicators), the BAFTA best picture has gone on to win the Oscar 9 times. This isn't a great indicator, but it's much better than the 20% we'd expect if they were unrelated. I'm eyeballing that this is statistically significant, so we'll go with it.

The revenant has a 70% chance of winning the Oscar for best picture. The revenant won big at the BAFTA movie awards ceremony. The U.K. film industry showered Valentine’s Day love on “The Revenant” Sunday, awarding the endurance epic five prizes, including best picture and best actor, at the British Academy Film Awards. This gives the revantent momentum leading up to the Oscars. However, one could argue that if there were awards given out for which movie looks like they went to the furtherst ends to create the film, sure, DiCaprio and the revanentwould be the only winner. But how much ‘acting’ does he actually do in The Revenant? Some critics don’t care how tough the production was, or how arduous the shooting schedule was and that you shouldn’t get an Oscar via attrition. It could be argued that this film did not have enough lines and extensive character dialogue to merit this award. Some of these factors could come into play while voting for the award. However, the odds are stacked in the revanents favor. The movie and its actors went to incredible heights to film this movie such as sleeping inside a dead animal, and coming close to getting life threatening frost bite. Not many movies would even attempt to put their actors through this, which is why this movie is so extraordinary. Other films such as the martian and spotlight could also get some votes and attention but the plots in these films are very predictable do not go have extreme scenes like in the Revenant. Some movie critics are already claiming that the revanent to win the oscars, putting his chances of winning at about 70%.

Leonardo Decaprio has a 70% chance of winning the Oscar for best picture. Leonardo won big at the BAFTA movie awards ceremony. The U.K. film industry showered Valentine’s Day love on “The Revenant” Sunday, awarding the endurance epic five prizes, including best picture and best actor, at the British Academy Film Awards. This gives Leonardo momentum leading up to the Oscars. However, one could argue that if there were awards given out for which actor looks like he went through the most hardship in making a movie, sure, DiCaprio would be the only winner. But how much ‘acting’ does he actually do in The Revenant? Some critics don’t care how tough the production was, or how arduous the shooting schedule was and that you shouldn’t get an Oscar via attrition. It could be argued that Leonardo did not have enough lines and extensive character dialogue to merit this award. Some of these factors could come into play while voting for the award. However, the odds are stacked in Leonardo's favor. He went to incredible heights to film this movie such as sleeping inside a dead animal, and coming close to getting life threatening frost bite. Not many actors would even attempt to do this, which is why this performance is so extraordinary. Other films such as the martian and spotlight could also get some votes and attention but the actors in these films do not go to the extremes in which Leonardo does in the Revenant. Leonardo also won best performance in the golden globes, giving more reason to believe that he will win. Some movie critics are already claiming that he is a lock to win the oscars, putting his chances of winning at about 70%.

- PGA predicts historically 73% of the academy award best picture winner (The Big Short). - DGA predicts it 90% of the times for the director and 81% of the time for the film (Iñarritu/Revenant). - 4 times there was a missmatch between these awards. 50% of the times the PGA predicted it, 50% of the times the DGA. - SAGA is the worst predictor historically (Spotlight) - However, ever since the PGA changed its voting method to that of the Academy, the match between its winner and that of the Acadamy is 7/7 (100%). - The only film winner of the Academy award not having a screenplay nomination is Titanic. This plays bad for Revenant and good for The big short and Spotlight, which do have a nomination on this category. - When a film has 12 or more nominations (Revenant) it usually wins the Academy award; however, it has always been the case that it also wins the PGA, so this year is not the case. - The greater group present in the Academy voting members are actors, which turned out to favor Spotlight.

Moving Revenant up 10% at the expense of The Big Short after the former won the Directors' Guild Award, which is one of the more reliable predictors of an Oscar. Against it, however, is that only three directors in the entire history of the Oscars have won the Best Picture Oscar in successive years.

The Revenant won the coveted Director's Guild Award which puts it back at the forefront of the race. But I still think it's crowded at the top. There are good changes we can have another Crash year. After The Revenant win at the DGA, The Guardian called the race unpredictable (mainly because the top awards given in the industry went to different films). Can the GJP prove them wrong? A good indicator is the usual buzz at film festivals (Toronto, Sundance, Berlin) but I didn't attend this year. So, here is what I'm looking at: -SPOLIGHT won the Screen Actors Guild Award and the Critics Choice. -THE BIG SHORT won the Producer's Guild (which some times has gone along with the Academy when the DGA has deviated). -MAD MAX is still the critic's darling (included in many top 10 lists) but it wasn't nominated for best film at BAFTA which takes away points since, in recent years, they tend to go along with the Academy, at least in nominations. -THE REVENANT'S weakest point is the script (one major category in which it didn't get a nom). -SPOTLIGHT has the best shot to get the award for best original script, and likewise, The BIG SHORT has the edge for best adapted screenplay. -SPOTLIGHT, overall, is superbly crafted and carries a heavy moral weight. The film's script should satisfy the Academy intellectually and emotionally. I don't want to get into criticism here but the film reaches very far in terms of society and something the Academy loves "the human experience." But is this topic in now or would the Hollywood elite have a more pressing issue in mind to push? That matters. -MAD MAX has a female lead in a year where gender equality is one of the most talked about issues and that gives it points. This film got 10 noms overall, only second to REVENANT. Production design of the film and a lot of technical aspects give it a lot of points as well. - As for the BIG SHORT, there is a big demand for tv shows, docs and films about the financial crisis. It has one of the best scripts of the year and in many ways it's a difficult film to make well. - The REVENANT is by all measures a directorial feat and has the most noms of all this year, 12, but I have doubts about its overall depth or its transcendence beyond the look at its main character. I'm not sure we can tell all that much about humanity just by looking at Glass. Nature is the protagonist in the film and in many ways it can serve as a great metaphor. I still have doubts about the clarity of it's depth and frankly, unrelenting suffering can get a little tiring. Of them all, this ss the most difficult movie to make but a lot of people say they don't vote for a film based on that. -The DGA is traditionally the best predictor for the Academy Award (it's as old as the Oscars and I think it has only picked a different film 13 times) but in those years where it has picked a different film, the Producer's Guild has sided with the Oscar pick. It is notable that the SAG is the largest branch of the Academy yet their record in predicting best picture is not great (this could be because they give award to actors individually and then to a film's cast ensemble). The Golden Globes are not as good predictors as the DGA. With that in mind, and pending the BAFTA on Feb 14, I am giving Spotlight the edge for best pic. It only got 6 nom overall, just like Big Short, while the Revenant got 12 but I think that is because of the types of films that they are.

Difficult to know what to do. In the past 12 years, the winner of the PGA Award for Outstanding Producer of a Theatrical Motion Picture has predicted the Oscar winner for Best Picture 9 times. That would be "The Big Short" this year. The three exceptions were "The Aviator", which lost to "Million Dollar Baby" in 2004; "Brokeback Mountain", which lost to "Crash" in 2005; and "Little Miss Sunshine", which lost to "The Departed" in 2006.
